  "prompt": "What is the difference between interim and ad interim order?",
  "response": "An interim order and an ad interim order are legal terms that both refer to temporary orders made by a court, but they have distinct nuances.\n\n**Interim Order:**\nAn interim order is issued by a court to provide immediate, temporary relief while the case is pending and until a final judgment is reached. This order typically remains effective until the court renders another, more comprehensive decision or until the matter is resolved.\n\n**Ad Interim Order:**\nAn ad interim order is also a temporary order, but it often refers to an order granted for a provisional period during the pendency of a petition for an interim order. It might be issued when a quick decision is required until the court can conduct a more detailed hearing and determine whether an interim order should be granted.\n\n**Key Differences:**\n\n1. **Duration:**\n   - **Interim Order:** Lasts until the conclusion of the case or until another order supersedes it.\n   - **Ad Interim Order:** Lasts until the court decides whether to issue an interim order or holds a further hearing.\n\n2. **Purpose:**\n   - **Interim Order:** Seeks to provide temporary relief with more consideration of the case\u2019s merits.\n   - **Ad Interim Order:** Offers immediate, short-term relief pending further main relief or interim order examination.\n\n**Example Scenario:**\nSuppose a party requests an injunction to stop a harmful action. The court might issue an ad interim order to halt the action immediately until a hearing for the interim order can be held. If the interim order is granted, it will continue to provide temporary relief until the final decision of the case.\n\nIn essence, both types of orders serve as temporary measures, but ad interim suggests an even more provisional state before the interim situation is fully addressed.",
